This folder contains my learning notes and hands-on practice from network scanning using Nmap. These skills are essential for identifying live hosts, open ports, and running services —
which is important for vulnerability assessment and network defense.

✅ Topics I Learned
🔹 What is Network Scanning?
The process of discovering active devices and services in a network.
Helps security analysts find vulnerabilities or unknown devices.

🔹 Introduction to Nmap
Nmap (Network Mapper) is a free, powerful tool used to scan networks.
It can detect hosts, services, operating systems, and open ports.

🔹 Types of Nmap Scans I Learned:
Ping scan – to find live hosts
TCP SYN scan – to detect open TCP ports
UDP scan – to discover services that use UDP (like DNS or DHCP)
Version scan – to identify software versions running on ports
OS detection – to guess the operating system

🔹 Nmap Flags I Practiced:
-sS (SYN scan)
-sU (UDP scan)
-O (OS detection)
-A (Aggressive scan – all info)
-p (Scan specific ports)
-v (Verbose output)

🔹 Common Port Numbers
Port 80 – HTTP
Port 443 – HTTPS
Port 22 – SSH
Port 21 – FTP
Port 53 – DNS
Port 25 – SMTP

🔹 How to Read Nmap Output
I learned how to analyze scan results to identify:
Open ports
Running service
Possible vulnerabilities
Host information (like OS and uptime)

🔐 Why It Matters in Cybersecurity
Nmap is a foundational tool for both ethical hackers and security analysts. It helps detect misconfigurations, unauthorized services, or exposed systems.
Knowing how to use Nmap makes me better at threat detection, vulnerability analysis, and network defense.

